Hezkin G'Zule bent over his worktable, frowning in the dim light as he painstakingly stiched the snakeskins together.  A gentle cough sounded before him, and he looked up slowly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Pazin! By Hate, man, you've been gone a week, where in Innoruuk's name have you been?! And don't you ever knock?&quot;<br>
<br>
The cloaked figure before him chuckled softly:<br>
<br>
&quot;There was something that needed doing.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pushing the snakeskins aside, Hezkin leaned forward, examining his fellow rogue.<br>
<br>
&quot;The child, then -- you offered the brat to Lord Zexus as a sacrifice for Innoruuk?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Not exactly,&quot; Pazin admitted.<br>
<br>
&quot;You fool, Pazin! Rumor abound that Priests of Innoruuk are going to investigate our hall and dispose of us for being &quot;unworthy sons of Hate&quot; -- all because of your past &quot;indiscretions&quot;!  Gods, man! The wood elf girl I can understand, but the halfling? A halfling! That's vile!&quot;<br>
<br>
Silence answered the armorer, who then sighed.<br>
<br>
&quot;All right. What, then?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;My apprentices disposed of the girl, and I supervised the event.  Her head and bloody heart should prove a proper sacrifice to appease the Priests.  Perrir should be sufficiently ... satisfied.  Indeed, this feat was managed within the very walls of Tunare's sacred stronghold.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pazin's dark face split into a gleaming white smile, and he dumped the gory prizes onto the worktable before turning away and vanishing.<br>
